e -- t17 Pamphlets and Political Writing -- t18 ‘The whole of war is an atrocity’: Morgan Philips Price and First World War Reporting in the Ottoman/Russian Borderlands -- tV. Film and Broadcasting -- t19 Official War Films in Britain: THE BATTLE OF THE SOMME (1916), its Impact Then and its Meaning Today -- t20 Too Colossal to Be Dramatic: The Cinema of the Great War -- t21 Representations of the First World War in Contemporary British Television Drama -- t22 The Sound of War: Audio, Radio and the First World War -- tVI. Publishing and Material Culture -- t23 The British Publishing Industry and the First World War -- t24 Photography and the First World War -- t25 The Imperial War Museum and the Material Culture of the First World War, 1917–2014 -- t26 The Evolution of First World War Computer Games -- tCONTRIBUTORS -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA new exploration of literary and artistic responses to WW1 from 1914 to the presentThis authoritative reference work examines literary and artistic responses to the war’s upheavals across a wide range of media and genres, from poetry to pamphlets, sculpture to television documentary, and requiems to war reporting. Rather than looking at particular forms of artistic expression in isolation and focusing only on the war and inter-war period, the 26 essays collected in this volume approach artistic responses to the war from a wide variety of angles and, where appropriate, pursue their inquiry into the present day. In 6 sections, covering Literature, the Visual Arts, Music, Periodicals and Journalism, Film and Broadcasting, and Publishing and Material Culture, a wide range of original chapters from experts across literature and the arts examine what means and approaches were employed to respond to the shock of war as well as asking such key questions as how and why literary and artistic responses to the war have changed over time, and how far later works of art are responses not only to the war itself, but to earlier cultural production.Key FeaturesOffers new insights into the breadth and depth of artistic responses to WWIEstablishes links and parallels across a wide range of different media and genresEmphasises the development of responses in different fields from 1914 to the present  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Jun 2022) 0aArts and societyxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat BritainxGreat BritainxArtxHistory. 0aArts and societyzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aArts, Britishx20th century. 0aArts, Britishy20th century. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918vArt and the war. 0aWorld War, 1914-1918xArt and the war. 4aLiterary Studies. 7aHISTORY / Europe / Great Britain / General.2bisacsh1 aBaxter, Katherine Isobel, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aBaxter, Katherine Isobel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBrandon, Laura, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCundy, Alys, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDawson, Clara, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDean, Robert, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEinhaus, Ann-Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGrant, Peter, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHaggith, Toby, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHand, Richard J., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHanna, Emma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKelly, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKempshall, Chris, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/voca